 for bestpractices and # Payment Processing

## Overview
Develop a secure, scalable Payment Processing system integrated with Stripe to manage subscriptions and in-app purchases within QuestHabit. The system must support Stripe Billing for subscriptions, Stripe Checkout/Elements for card management, robust webhook handling for reconciliation, PCI-compliant tokenization (no raw card data stored), proration logic for plan changes, and retry logic for failed payments. Provide three interconnected user-facing pages (Checkout, Subscription Management, History) and server-side APIs to support real-time billing events, invoice retrieval, download of receipts, and billing detail views. Ensure strict runtime safety: null/undefined checks, nullish coalescing for API results, and typed states for arrays/objects.

---

## Components to Build
1. Stripe Integration Layer (Backend)
   - Create a service module to encapsulate Stripe operations:
     - Subscriptions: create, update (proration logic on plan upgrade/downgrade), cancel, suspend, resume.
     - Invoices: fetch, list, retrieve PDFs/receipts, download URLs.
     - Payment Methods: attach/detach, set default payment method, tokenization handling.
     - Checkout Sessions: create for one-time purchases and subscriptions, success/cancel redirects.
     - Webhooks: receive and verify events (invoice.paid, invoice.payment_failed, customer.subscription.updated, customer.subscription.deleted, charge.failed, etc.), reconcile local state, handle refunds.
   - Security: validate webhook signatures, use webhook secret from environment vars, replay protection, idempotency handling.
   - Data mapping: translate Stripe objects into app domain models; guard all access with Array.isArray and safe fallbacks (e.g., data ?? []).

2. API Layer (Backend)
   - REST/GraphQL endpoints to support frontend:
     - POST /api/payments/checkout-session (subscription or one-time)
     - POST /api/payments/attach-payment-method
     - POST /api/payments/set-default-payment-method
     - POST /api/payments/subscription (create/update/cancel)
     - GET /api/payments/invoices (list invoices for a customer)
     - GET /api/payments/invoices/:id (get invoice details)
     - GET /api/payments/invoices/:id/download (secure PDF download)
     - POST /api/payments/webhook (Stripe webhook endpoint)
     - GET /api/payments/subscription/upcoming-invoice (simulate upcoming invoice)
   - Validation: ensure inputs are validated, using default empty arrays/objects where appropriate; sanitize and guard against null responses (e.g., response?.data ?? []).
   - Database schema integration: store customerId, Stripe subscriptionId, paymentMethodId, invoice history, plan changes, proration periods, retry counts.

3. Frontend Pages and Components
   - page_billing_checkout
     - Flow: select plan or one-time purchase, collect payment via Stripe Elements/Checkout, handle 3D Secure where required, confirm success with receipt/download options.
     - Components: PlanSelector, BillingForm (Stripe Elements), SCA/3DS flow UI, CheckoutSummary, ConfirmationModal.
   - page_billing_subscription
     - Flow: manage existing subscription (change plan, upgrade/downgrade with proration), view upcoming invoices, pause/cancel, update billing details.
     - Components: SubscriptionCard, PlanChangeDrawer, BillingDetailsForm, UpcomingInvoicesPanel, CancelationPolicyNote.
   - page_billing_history
     - Flow: list invoices and receipts with status, amount, period, date; provide download link for PDFs; filter/sort; view billing details panel.
     - Components: InvoiceList, InvoiceRow, InvoiceDetailDrawer, DownloadButton, BillingAddressDetails.
   - Shared components:
     - PaymentMethodSelector (card last4, brand, default indicator)
     - ReceiptDownloadButton
     - InvoiceBadge (paid, unpaid, due)
     - LoadingSkeletons for invoices and payments
     - Toasts/Alerts for success or error states

4. Admin/Webhook Testing Tools (optional)
   - Webhook simulator UI to generate Stripe test events and verify local webhook handling.
   - Local test harness for end-to-end test of subscription lifecycle and payment retries.

---

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Use React with TypeScript and a strong types-first approach.
- State management: useState/useEffect with proper defaults; arrays initialized with []: useState<Type[]>([]). Guards: (items ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : [].
- Stripe integration:
  - Use Stripe.js and React Stripe Elements (or Stripe React SDK) for card data capture.
  - Avoid storing raw card data; use Stripe tokenization and attach payment methods securely.
  - Implement 3DS where required; handle confirmCardPayment with clientSecret.
- UI/UX:
  - Implement the design system from the Visual Style section (colors, typography, spacing, card styles, glow, shadows, gradients).
  - Cards: full-width, rounded radii 16–24px, frosted glass effect on light surfaces.
  - Primary CTAs: warm orange gradient (#FF9A57 → #FFD7A8); secondary buttons: outlined dark text with light borders.
  - Ensure responsive behavior: single-column layouts on mobile, with adequate padding (16–20px) and 8px grid multiples.
- Accessibility:
  - Proper aria-labels, semantic HTML for sections, headings, and controls.
  - Color contrast compliance for text and interactive elements.
- Security:
  - Do not expose Stripe secrets on the client; all sensitive actions occur via backend API calls.
  - Use CSRF protection where applicable, and ensure endpoints require user authentication (e.g., JWT or session-based).
- Validation:
  - Client-side validation for required fields; display inline errors.
  - Ensure all API responses are validated before usage (e.g., Array.isArray(data) ? data : []).
- Error handling:
  - Graceful fallbacks for API failures; show retry options and actionable error messages.

### Backend
- Language/Stack: Node.js with TypeScript (or your preferred stack) and a SQL/NoSQL database of choice.
- Database schema (examples):
  - users: id, email, stripeCustomerId, defaultPaymentMethodId, etc.
  - subscriptions: id, userId, stripeSubscriptionId, planId, status, currentPeriodStart, currentPeriodEnd, prorationInvoiceId, cancelAt, cancelAtPeriodEnd, etc.
  - invoices: id, userId, stripeInvoiceId, amountDue, amountPaid, currency, status, periodStart, periodEnd, pdfUrl, billingDetails
  - payment_methods: id, userId, stripePaymentMethodId, brand, last4, expMonth, expYear, isDefault, etc.
- Stripe integration:
  - Use Stripe SDK securely; manage billing cycles, proration, and retry logic.
  - Webhooks: implement a robust webhook handler, verify signatures, idempotent processing, and reconcile state with local DB. Handle events:
    - customer.subscription.created/updated/paused/resumed/canceled
    - invoice.created/paid/payment_failed/finalized
    - invoice.payment_succeeded
    - checkout.session.completed
    - payment_method.attached/detached/set_default
    - charge.failed (for one-time purchases)
  - Proration logic: when upgrading/downgrading, create or apply proration invoices as per Stripe recommendations; reflect upcoming invoice details in the UI.
  - Retry logic: configure automatic retries for failed invoices; expose retry options in UI and reflect status changes.
- Security and compliance:
  - PCI-DSS aligned: use Stripe Elements/Checkout; never store raw card data.
  - Webhook secrets stored securely; rotate periodically; log webhook events with minimal sensitive data.
- API design:
  - Endpoints should enforce authentication and authorization checks.
  - Consistent response shapes; guard all array/object accesses with data ?? [] or Array.isArray(data) ? data.map(...) : [].
  - Data validation: sanitize inputs; validate IDs, prices, plan IDs; return meaningful error codes.
- Testing:
  - Unit tests for Stripe service wrappers and webhook handlers.
  - End-to-end tests simulating complete lifecycle: checkout, subscription creation, plan change with proration, invoice paid, payment failed, receipt download.
  - Integration tests with Stripe test mode (using test API keys and test cards).

### Integration
- Flow orchestration:
  - Frontend invokes API to create a checkout session; Stripe handles payment method capture; backend finalizes subscription/invoice data and returns a clientSecret or success state.
  - Webhook events update local DB; push notifications or UI updates reflect changes (invoices, upcoming charges, plan changes).
  - History page fetches invoices from backend; receipts download via authenticated endpoints.
  - Checkout supports both subscription and one-time purchases; ensure separate handling and UI distinction.
- Data safety:
  - All API responses that return lists should guard against null by using data ?? [] and using Array.isArray checks where appropriate.
  - Use destructuring with defaults: const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {}.

---

## User Experience Flow

1. User lands on Billing Overview (root payments page).
   - See current subscription status, next billing date, next amount, and quick actions (Change Plan, Cancel, Add Payment Method).
   - See recent invoices with status badges and download receipts.

2. Checkout / Purchase
   - User selects a subscription plan or a one-time product.
   - User enters payment details via Stripe Elements; completes 3D Secure if required.
   - Backend creates Stripe Checkout Session or Payment Intent; user completes payment on Stripe UI.
   - On success: show confirmation with receipt/download link; update user’s subscription state, show upcoming invoice details.

3. Manage Subscription (page_billing_subscription)
   - User chooses to upgrade/downgrade or change billing cadence/plan.
   - System computes proration; user previews impact (proration credit or additional charge).
   - User confirms; backend updates subscription; Stripe handles proration invoice; local state updates after webhook confirms.

4. Invoice History (page_billing_history)
   - User views a list of invoices and receipts with filters (date range, status).
   - User can click to view details and download PDF receipts securely (requires authentication).

5. Webhook Synchronization (Server-side)
   - Stripe events are received securely; local DB updated to reflect invoices, subscriptions, and payment status.
   - In-app notifications surface for successful payments, failed payments, or upcoming charges.

6. Error Handling and Support
   - If payment fails, show clear messaging and options to retry or update payment method.
   - Provide a retry workflow for failed invoices via Stripe and reflect status in UI.

---

## Technical Specifications

Data Models (Schema details)
- User
  - id: string
  - email: string
  - stripeCustomerId: string | null
  - defaultPaymentMethodId: string | null
- Plan
  - id: string
  - stripePriceId: string
  - name: string
  - amount: number
  - currency: string
  - interval: 'monthly' | 'yearly'
- Subscription
  - id: string
  - userId: string
  - stripeSubscriptionId: string
  - planId: string
  - status: string
  - currentPeriodStart: number (epoch)
  - currentPeriodEnd: number (epoch)
  - cancelAt?: number
  - cancelAtPeriodEnd?: boolean
  - prorationInvoiceId?: string
- Invoice
  - id: string
  - userId: string
  - stripeInvoiceId: string
  - amountDue: number
  - amountPaid: number
  - currency: string
  - status: string
  - periodStart: number
  - periodEnd: number
  - pdfUrl?: string
  - billingDetails?: object
- PaymentMethod
  - id: string
  - userId: string
  - stripePaymentMethodId: string
  - brand: string
  - last4: string
  - expMonth: number
  - expYear: number
  - isDefault: boolean

API Endpoints (Routes and methods)
- POST /api/payments/checkout-session
  - Body: { userId, type: 'subscription'|'one_time', planId?, priceId?, successUrl, cancelUrl }
  - Response: { sessionId, clientSecret, url }
- POST /api/payments/attach-payment-method
  - Body: { userId, paymentMethodId }
- POST /api/payments/set-default-payment-method
  - Body: { userId, paymentMethodId }
- POST /api/payments/subscription
  - Body: { userId, action: 'create'|'update'|'cancel', planId?, proration?: boolean }
- GET /api/payments/invoices
  - Query: { userId, limit, startingAfter }
- GET /api/payments/invoices/:id
  - Response: { invoice object }
- GET /api/payments/invoices/:id/download
  - Requires auth; returns signed URL or stream for PDF
- POST /api/payments/webhook
  - Stripe webhook endpoint; processes events
- GET /api/payments/subscription/upcoming-invoice
  - Query: { userId, upcomingOnly?: boolean }
- Optional admin endpoints for webhook status, retry logs, etc.

Security
- Authentication: JWTs or session-based; all endpoints require user authentication.
- Stripe webhooks: use Stripe-Signature header; verify with webhook secret.
- Data access: enforce row-level permissions; ensure users only access their own data.
- Data Minimization: avoid exposing sensitive data; store only necessary Stripe IDs and metadata.
- PCI compliance: do not collect or store raw card data on server; rely on Stripe tokenization.

Validation
- Use strict input validation on all endpoints.
- Always guard array/object usage with (data ?? []) or Array.isArray(data) ? data.map(...) : [].
- Use safe access patterns: const invoices = Array.isArray(apiResponse?.invoices) ? apiResponse.invoices : [].
- Destructure with defaults: const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {}.

Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Stripe integration successfully creates subscriptions, handles checkout sessions, and manages one-time purchases with secure tokenization.
- [ ] Webhook handler correctly reconciles Stripe events to local DB, including subscription lifecycle, invoices, and payment retries.
- [ ] Frontend pages render accurate billing information, allow plan changes with correct proration logic, and provide downloadable receipts as PDFs.
- [ ] All API responses robustly guard against null/undefined values; array results default to [] using data ?? [] and Array.isArray checks.
- [ ] User flows pass end-to-end tests in Stripe test mode, including 3DS where required and successful invoice payments.
- [ ] Accessibility and design system guidelines are followed across all pages with responsive behavior.

UI/UX Guidelines
- Apply the provided design system and Visual Style:
  - Colors: primary orange gradient (#FF9A57 → #FFD7A8) for CTAs; deep violet (#7C61FF) for secondary accents; peach-cream backgrounds; dark mode variant (#11121A) for emphasis cards.
  - Typography: Poppins/Inter-like rounded sans; headings heavy (700), body 400, labels 500.
  - Components: rounded cards (16–24px radius), frosted glass effect on light surfaces, soft shadows, gradients in hero/summary cards, bottom navigation with centered FAB for quick actions.
  - Data visualizations: soft bar charts with rounded ends, gradients, light grid lines, sparkline mini-charts.
  - Interactive states: hover/press lift, CTA glow, micro-interactions for achievements.

Accessible and scalable architecture
- Componentize UI: PlanSelector, StripePaymentForm, InvoiceList, SubscriptionManager, ReceiptDownloader, etc.
- Localization-ready strings; support multiple currencies if needed.
- Logging, monitoring, and error reporting hooks for payment events.
- Proper unit and integration tests for frontend and backend logic.

---

## Deliverables

- Fully implemented Stripe-based payment processing with:
  - Frontend Stripe Elements integration for card capture and 3DS flows.
  - Backend Stripe service layer with subscription, invoice, payment method management, and webhook handling.
  - Secure, authenticated API endpoints for checkout, subscriptions, and invoices.
  - Webhook endpoint with signature verification and idempotent processing.
- Three connected pages:
  - page_billing_checkout
  - page_billing_subscription
  - page_billing_history
- Data models and migrations for users, subscriptions, invoices, and payment methods.
- Comprehensive tests:
  - Unit tests for Stripe service and webhook logic.
  - Integration tests for end-to-end flows in Stripe test mode.
- Documentation:
  - Developer README detailing setup, environment variables (Stripe keys, webhook secret), and data model mapping.
  - API reference with endpoint descriptions, expected payloads, and error handling.

Note: Ensure all generated code adheres to the runtime safety rules outlined, especially guarding against null/undefined values before using array methods and initializing React useState with proper defaults. Use data ?? [] for Supabase results or equivalent backend query results, Array.isArray checks, and destructuring defaults as described. for style.

CRITICAL DESIGN REQUIREMENTS:
- You MUST follow ALL design principles and patterns specified in the Design Reference above
- Do NOT deviate from the design specifications without explicit user permission
- Implement ALL visual design elements (colors, typography, spacing, shadows, animations) as specified
- Follow the layout patterns and component designs exactly as documented
- Ensure all interactions and micro-animations match the reference specifications

CRITICAL TECHNICAL REQUIREMENTS:
- React 18.3.1, React Router 6.30.1
- Tailwind CSS v3 with tailwind.config.js and custom keyframes
- @tailwindcss/typography plugin for rich text content
- Tailwind CSS animations (NOT Motion library or framer-motion)
- Sonner for toasts
- Recharts for data visualization
- Native fetch() with API utilities in src/lib/api.ts
- Design system with CSS custom properties
- Use RGB color values for theming
- When Supabase is configured: use Edge Functions for LLM and server-only logic; never expose API keys in the client


=== EDGE FUNCTIONS & DATABASE MIGRATIONS (MANDATORY) ===

Even without a Supabase project connected, you MUST create the correct files when the task requires them:

EDGE FUNCTIONS - create supabase/functions/<function-name>/index.ts for:
- LLM/AI features (chat, completions, embeddings, vector search)
- Third-party API integrations (Stripe, SendGrid, Twilio, OpenAI, Anthropic, etc.)
- Incoming webhooks from external services
- Any server-only logic or logic that must not expose secrets to the client
- Any prompt that says "create edge function" or "add edge function"
File location: supabase/functions/<function-name>/index.ts
Import pattern: import { serve } from "https://deno.land/std@0.168.0/http/server.ts";
Never expose API keys or secrets in client-side code.

DATABASE MIGRATIONS - create supabase/migrations/<YYYYMMDDHHmmss>_<description>.sql for:
- Every new database table, view, or enum mentioned in the task
- Every schema change (ALTER TABLE, new index, new policy, etc.)
- Any prompt that says "create migration" or describes a data model
Make migrations idempotent (IF NOT EXISTS / CREATE OR REPLACE). Include RLS policies.
Do NOT run "supabase db push" or execute SQL directly — only create the .sql files.

MANDATORY CHECKLIST - Before finishing, verify:
- [ ] Migration SQL file(s) created for every database table/schema change mentioned
- [ ] Edge Function file(s) created for every server-side/secrets feature mentioned
- [ ] TypeScript types created for every new database table

